%I A393126 #29 Apr 01 2026 11:29:20
%S A393126 5,14,24,33,53,80,83,240,252,295,328,519,545,757,1463,2462,2493,2936,
%T A393126 3597,4071
%N A393126 Numbers k such that there exists m < k/2 such that 10^k - 10^m - 1 is a reversible prime; i.e., a palindromic prime or an emirp.
%C A393126 The corresponding emirps have k-1 digits 9 and one digit 8, occurring after the leftmost resp. rightmost m digits.
%C A393126 The reverse of 10^k - 10^m - 1 is A004086(10^k - 10^m - 1) = 10^k - 10^(k-m-1) - 1, which is a palindromic wing prime (PWP) rather than an emirp when the digit 8 is exactly in the middle, i.e., if m = (k-1)/2. This is obviously allowed by the condition m < k/2.
%C A393126 The digit sum A007953(10^k - 10^m - 1) = 9*k - 1 is never divisible by 3, so the terms can have any residue modulo 3. Also for all other n = 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, ..., all possible residues (mod n) appear to occur, mostly quite early.
%C A393126 The latest residue (mod 3) to occur is 1, for a(10) = 295 (== 1 [mod 3]).
%C A393126 The latest residue (mod 5) to occur is 2, for a(14) = 757 (== 2 [mod 5]), which corresponds to the first PWP (with m = 378 = (k-1)/2).
%C A393126 The residue 2 (mod 8) does not occur among the terms below 1000. Does it ever occur, and if so, when?
%e A393126 For k = 1, 2, 3, 4, we don't have any such emirp.
%e A393126 For k = 5 and m = 1, we have 10^k-10^m-1 = 99989 which is prime as is 98999.
%e A393126 For k = 14, m = 5, we have 10^k-10^m-1 = 99999999899999 which is an emirp as well.
%o A393126 (PARI) is_A393126(n, r=10^n-1)=for(m=1,n\/2-1, ispseudoprime(r-10^m) && ispseudoprime(r-10^(n-m-1))&& return(m)) \\ return the m-value if it exists, else 0
%o A393126 for(k=1,oo, is_A393126(k) && print1(k","))
%Y A393126 Cf. A006567 (emirps), A004086 (n with digits reversed).
%Y A393126 Cf. A020472 (primes with only digits 8 and 9), A173594 (near-repdigit emirps), A128389 (emirps with only composite digits).
%Y A393126 Cf. A263431 (near-repdigit primes with only digits 9 and a single 8).
%K A393126 nonn,base,hard,more
%O A393126 1,1
